                type="document" xml:id="d271">
                <head>271. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>In a letter to Chairman <persName corresp="#p_KAN1">Kosygin</persName> dated May
                    2, 1968, President <persName corresp="#p_JLB1">Johnson</persName> proposed that
                    the Soviet and U.S. Governments announce during the debate then underway in the
                    United Nations General Assembly over the Non-Proliferation Treaty “that they
                    have agreed to begin bilateral negotiations on an agreement to limit strategic
                    offensive and defensive missiles.” For text, see <ref
                        target="frus1964-68v11#d237">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations,</hi> 1964–1968, volume XI, Document
                        237</ref>. <persName corresp="#p_KAN1">Kosygin</persName> replied in a June
                    21 letter to <persName corresp="#p_JLB1">Johnson</persName> that the Soviets
                    “attach great importance” to “questions concerning restraint in the strategic
                    arms race” and they hoped “before long it will be possible more concretely to
                    exchange views.” The President responded the next day, proposing to <persName
                        corresp="#p_KAN1">Kosygin</persName> that they jointly announce on July
                    1—the day the Non-Proliferation Treaty would be opened for signature—an
                    “agreement to hold talks on the strategic missile problem.” <persName
                        corresp="#p_KAN1">Kosygin</persName> accepted the proposal in a June 27
                    letter to <persName corresp="#p_JLB1">Johnson</persName>. For text of their
                    exchanges are June 21, 22, and 27, see <ref target="frus1964-68v11#d247">ibid.,
                        Documents 247</ref>–<ref target="frus1964-68v11#d249">249</ref>.</p>
            </div>
